#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.finfo:102
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.finfo:103
msgid ""
"For developers of NumPy: do not instantiate this at the module level. The "
"initial calculation of these parameters is expensive and negatively impacts "
"import times.  These objects are cached, so calling ``finfo()`` repeatedly "
"inside your functions is not a problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.finfo:108
msgid ""
"Note that ``smallest_normal`` is not actually the smallest positive "
"representable value in a NumPy floating point type. As in the IEEE-754 "
"standard [R2ee89c7f792a-1]_, NumPy floating point types make use of "
"subnormal numbers to fill the gap between 0 and ``smallest_normal``. "
"However, subnormal numbers may have significantly reduced precision "
"[R2ee89c7f792a-2]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.finfo:114
msgid ""
"For ``longdouble``, the representation varies across platforms. On most "
"platforms it is IEEE 754 binary128 (quad precision) or binary64-extended (80-"
"bit extended precision). On PowerPC systems, it may use the IBM double-"
"double format (a pair of float64 values), which has special characteristics "
"for precision and range."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.finfo:120
msgid ""
"This function can also be used for complex data types as well. If used, the "
"output will be the same as the corresponding real float type (e.g. numpy."
"finfo(numpy.csingle) is the same as numpy.finfo(numpy.single)). However, the "
"output is true for the real and imaginary components."
msgstr ""

